Bozon Higgs in detail
Last summer, the report that the scientists may have managed to find the bozon Higgs, caused a real excitement - and not without reason.
It is believed that this bozon explains the mass of all particles in the Universe, not much.
In addition, this is the last particle, the existence of which was predicted within the framework of the Standard model - our best, or, at least, the "have the least imperfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not been previously experienced.
But physicists are not yet fully sure that it is the bozone of Higgs.
We know, without a shadow of doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the bozon Higgs, predicted by the Standard model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at one major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although for the full confidence of some data is not yet available.
Let us imagine that we are talking about the bosom of Higgs, as the chances of mistakes seem minimal, and see what it means.
There is, in this world one law is quite inevitable, which states that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
By bya, this rule is not possible, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will harm yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it also has one law of a similar nature: the principle of exclusion of Paulie, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general, in some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens, called ferments, who prudently obey the Paulian principle.
In the other fuss bozones, the heinous gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything - at least to this principle, which means that they can calmly be in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (by the way, completely extraordinary) Particle Adventure Berkeley Lab, these bozones are divided, in turn, into two groups: mezzans, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of force," through which the main forces of nature spread and to which in some way belongs Bozon Higgs.
These very bozones, it should be emphasized, not all such exotic creatures, as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal bozone: a photon, or "particle of light," which is a "courier" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when one particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "breaks" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, approximately like a stone thrown into the pond.
From this "violation" is born electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and, therefore, one of the bozones of "power carriers."
A more stable field
The same happens to the bozon of Higgs, with the only difference that in order for this bozon to appear, there must be "breaked" another field, the field of Higgs.
However, the field of Higgs is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to extly it, it is necessary to achieve very and very high energies, as if it were about a frozen pond, the surface of which could shake only a very large stone.
That is why a huge particle accelerator is needed, as the one that is operated in CERN - the Great Adron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! - to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the bosun Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others - no: a sheet of paper, for example, will never stay on the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact, have mass, while others (as a photon, by the way) do not have it.
So, what "can bring" all these studies, asks Mrs. Plomondon?
In science they are used to check the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between the results of observations and forecasts of CM.
In addition, some of them are eager to find such a divergence, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door for "new physics" and shut up some of the holes of Models.
The latter, I must say, still has significant flaws, not offering any explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the Universe (oh!).
But so far, CERN has not found such a split.
Effects
The use of these studies for the daily life of the average person is more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
See: in the early 60s, laser pioneers in the laboratories of Bella could not even assume what revolution they would cause their work.
They foresaw their applications in science, but no more than that.
In fact, the already late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the laboratories of Bella, where in 1960 was invented laser, and which himself developed the first continuous laser (presighted were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered rather as a "laboratory gadget."
Imagine...
And in addition, the application can be found for the tools that accompany the study.
For example, the same Willard Boyle during his optical studies in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras of the world and deserved the Nobel Prize in Physics of 2009.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Adron Collider will definitely change our life, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
