Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ECA on September 12, 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with the ECA in 1994 and over the next years took an active part in a number of projects of the agency.
But the path to space Poland began a lot earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights to space, but it was not always met with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, about the lecture by A.Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 represented in the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his innovative work "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
The young engineer's ideology (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gademsky was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltri and Andre Luis Hirsche for the "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Hadomsky became a well-known world propagandist of cosmonautics, and his contribution was appreciated, including by the fact that one of the craters on the back of the Moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway rail was built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not clear even, a rocket was to be used to disperse or to braking the trolley.
Information about this Dresine is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The study was carried out by the armament equipment section in cooperation with professors Mechislaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokzhitsky.
From the surviving materials it is clear that the studies have reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of the German troops the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter missile proposed by engineer Rogozinski appeared in a specialized press, and next year the work of the "Air torpedo missile and aircraft bomb" by the author of Leliva-Kizoblotsky was launched.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war all projects of military use of rocket equipment was carried out by the Temporary Scientific and Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated the whole work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its work, the work ended due to the beginning of the war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronzystwo Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time the society is mentioned in the November issue of 1954, the magazine "Problems," which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will deal with astronautics.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites were gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research is a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautics Society (POA) has tried to join the international astronautics federation (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn of the PIA became its valid member.
And next year, the first chairman of the PA Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became the deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
In this position he remained until his death, which came in 1959.
Since 1956, the PIA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish missile to perform scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable of overcoming a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bladovoy wasteland.
This missile was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The heir of the first RM missiles was Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designed as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket was a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1V - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 l.
The maximum range of flight in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed a Meteor-2 missile, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to bring out a payload weighing 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the KOSPAR (Committ on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the National Committee of KOSPAR two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland participated in space explorations on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
