Germany abstained from voting for the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, acting so, Berlin balances on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against Palestinians" application for the status of an observer to the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from voting.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be cautious in connection with its special relations with Israel.
But at the same time I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without speaking too critical to Israel.
During the Libyan Upris in March 2011, Germany also refrained from voting for the introduction of a restricted zone for flights.
As a result, NATO made this proposal.
Germany finds it difficult to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, that's it.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, moving from a policy, which, so to speak, was managed by the United States, to the actual German foreign policy.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coordinated unified policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they only find their role, but are on the way to "more normal" foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy as France or the UK pursues.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
This is a willingness to take a position in its national interests, not depending on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that the German foreign policy depends on the economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are largely different from the interests of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it is necessary to exercise caution in order not to offend the public and elites in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not a completely unilateral connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Did Germany have its relationship with the United States, abstaining in making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that the understanding of the German position prevails in Europe and even the United States.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as in the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even acquire this particular respect.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the contrary, the United States clearly supported the veto.
Is there a discrepancy between the United States and many European states?
Due to the American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government has a sufficient understanding of the European position in the depths of our hearts.
But in connection with the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences in opinions are not as significant as it always seems.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not delighted with Netanyahu's policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be somewhat easier for the Germans if there was a united, consistent European policy, but now it is not so.
Therefore, they cannot act within a broader approach and are forced to act instead, relying only on their own vision of the situation.
That is how they come with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take a leading role in the development of a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of ties with Israel.
This topic has always been tickling.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take the main role?
Or is Germany still a difficult role?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to this, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, is still difficult to play a significant role.
Let's consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes an important role, there are a variety of anti-German feelings.
It is not easy for the Germans to cope with this.
Actually, this is an old problem: you do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much heavier position than the United States.
It should take into account various neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the influence of the United States in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans will just have to play a more significant role.
Even if you do not like it, it is unpleasant or amplifies the dislike for you - this is life!
Stephen Sabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution in which academicians and political experts from Europe and North America jointly investigate the problems of the transatlantic community.
