Old battles in the new Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas may become a fragile foundation for further peace
Is there a long-term peace between the Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
The next round of bloodshed pushes to the conclusion of the futility of such hopes.
There are common, meaningless disputes about who the first started; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians have been killed, most of whom were civilians, and six Israelis; for the first time during the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel Aviv and the sacred city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are unhinged in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the "Arab Spring" have been erected in a rebellious storm of established realities, and the Palestinians and Israelis have not managed to stay away from the wits that shocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope to get out of this deadly deadlock.
The war without victories
At first glance, the current situation does not give reason for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, the agreement on which was signed on November 21, the clashes that took place this week only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, who came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say that they have forced Israel to retreat despite their losses.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the group were destroyed, and 1.7 million residents are blocked in one of the most densely populated and problematic corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining popularity in the West Bank - another Palestinian territory controlled by the currently more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that the time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and rich friends.
The reviving regional leader of Turkey, who was once the closest ally of Israel among Muslim countries, supported Hamas; its example was followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most rapidly developing states of the Persian Gulf.
The cerevents of Hamas declare the creation of an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, in which the paramilitary group of Hezbollah rule, to Syria, in which increasingly the Islamic rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad's power, and then to Jordan, where the king's authorities are threatened by the allies of Hamas.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where under President Mohammed Mursi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood has strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to the support of Hamas.
The Muslim brothers, on the contrary, are the organization, in many ways similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice will not be able to stifle even Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the "hard" line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli anti-missile system Iron Dome justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the missiles launched by Hamas.
Citizens of Israel can sleep quietly, at least for some time.
As for diplomacy, the U.S. remained loyal to its unchanging position; many European countries also blamed the beginning of the last round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially in the government of Binyamin Netanyahu, which largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, approximately 30 Israelis have been killed by missiles fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide terrorists, partly at the expense of the wall that enters the West Bank of the Jordan River - a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from the point of view of international legislation.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - united with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of indulging in the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they give all power in the West Bank, will they not start launching missiles from there towards Israel, as do their fellows in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and firmly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps the supporters of the "hard" line will win; but their calculations may be refuted by the Arab spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not feel the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense part of Israel's budget is greater than all its Arab neighbors, combined.
The unleashing of war with the regional superpower is unlikely to help the Arab governments to strengthen their own economy.
The Pragueism of the President of Egypt, Mursi, who together with Barack Obama worked on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to no less, should take into account the long-term consequences of its policy.
As democratic changes in the Arab countries, the deprivation of the right to self-determination of Palestinians is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israel's occupied territories, like a bus blown up in Tel Aviv this week.
Repressions already undermine the foundations of democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to pay the growing dissatisfaction of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse
There is only a decision that is steadlessly called by sound representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and concessions to Israel territories in exchange for security.
There is hope that not too impressive in the short term - the hope that the ceasefire will allow other countries to more effectively influence the parties of the conflict.
Egypt, which has long decided to block the supply of weapons to Gaza, as well as Turkey and Qatar have more than ever a favorable position to convince Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the joint use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah's movements.
This would make it more for the establishment of a Palestinian state than the upcoming vote in the United Nations, the result of which could be the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama must also play his role in seating Israel at the negotiating table.
During his first term, he did not present his own plan of peaceful settlement.
After returning to the White House, he still demonstrates his reluctance to connect to the solution of this problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australia has entered into force the law on a unified package for cigarettes.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the images of body parts affected by diseases are contrastingly on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in the world practice Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco came into force, replacing logos and color design of different brands of the same box of duly olive color with terrible pictures of body parts affected by disease and images of children whose health is undermined by smoking of their parents.
In addition to different pictures and inscriptions warning about the harm of smoking, the only difference between packs introduced mandatory from this Saturday - the names of brands that are printed in the same small font.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the registration of tobacco packaging.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the purpose of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving this harmful habit of fashion status.
Such a decision was based on the results of studies showing that people who did not smoke up to 26 years, in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
"It is obvious that even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging," explains the Minister of Health Tanya Plibersec, referring to the studies showing that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the world's smallest share of smokers, so these changes will not particularly affect the profits of multinational corporations, but the possibility of such measures is already considered by other countries.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market, which will sell cheap and affordable cigarettes.
"This law will lead to serious consequences other than those that were conceived by its initiators," said Scott McIntayre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of fake products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For someone, on the contrary, new laws contribute to business growth.
Sandra Ha from a small family company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for portigars and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on the package, has grown rapidly (practically from scratch) since two months ago such companies as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case in the high court of Australia, where they tried to appeal this law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesale enterprises and expects a new party.
